04817nam a22007695i 9789814695053DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898146950537 a10.1355/97898146950532doi  a(DE-B1597)522115  a(OCoLC)1100438724  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aSOC0070002bisacsh04a331.12795932231 aJirattikorn, Amporn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aManaging Migration in Myanmar and Thailand :bEconomic Reforms, Policies, Practices and Challenges /cAmporn Jirattikorn. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (28 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tManaging Migration in Myanmar and Thailand: Economic Reforms, Policies, Practices and Challenges -- tManaging Migration in Myanmar and Thailand: Economic Reforms, Policies, Practices and Challenges -- tREFERENCES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe migrant workforce in Thailand, the majority of whom are from Myanmar, is an integral part of the economy. The changing economic and political landscapes in both Myanmar and Thailand demand an assessment of the impact these changes will have on the migration patterns of Myanmar nationals.Over the last two decades, the ineffective and ambiguous registration programmes have produced gaps between policy goals and outcomes.Under the current military regime, Thailand's policy towards migration remains unclear and as a result creates fear and uncertainty among foreign migrants. Myanmar also lacks a comprehensive and holistic migration policy. The new civilian government has begun to work with the Thai government through the process of regularization. Nonetheless, the policy reflects a short-term approach rather than a broader more long-term migrant worker policy.The recent developments in Myanmar raises concerns about the availability of the supply of migrants from Myanmar and the impact these transformations may have on Thailand's economy. The return of a large number of Myanmar migrants could result in labour shortage in Thailand, an increase in the cost of migrant labour, and an eventual increase in the cost of production. A large wave of returnees could make it difficult for Myanmar to provide enough jobs to accommodate them. Further, foreign remittance payments from Myanmar workers are a large source of revenue for the Myanmar government and the return of a large number of Myanmar migrants would result in significant financial losses for the government.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEmigration & Immigration. 0aForeign workers, Burmese—Thailand—Government policy. 0aMyanmar—Economic policy. 0aMyanmar—Emigration and immigration—Government policy. 0aThailand—Emigration and immigration—Government policy. 4aEmigration & Immigration. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066300608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060667640uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981469505340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814695053423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814695053.jpg  a978-3-11-060667-6  ISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017c2015d2017  a978-3-11-066300-6  ISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  